2026-05-25 | Jump Game VII

Question
Return true if reaching last index is possible.
	Key Insight
Naively checking all jumps for every index
would become:
		O(n × range)
Too slow for n = 100000.
Optimization:
		use sliding window count
		to track reachable positions.
	Approach
1.	Create reachable array:
		dp[i] =
			can we reach i?
2.	dp[0] = true
3.	Maintain:
		count of reachable indices
		inside current valid jump window
4.	For each index i:
		add:
				dp[i-minJump]
		remove:
				dp[i-maxJump-1]
5.	If:
		window count > 0
		and s[i]=='0'
		then:
				dp[i]=true
6.	Return dp[n-1]
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    bool canReach(string s,
                  int minJump,
                  int maxJump) {
        int n = s.size();
        vector<bool> dp(n, false);
        dp[0] = true;
        int reachable = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++){
            // add new reachable index
            if(i - minJump >= 0 &&
               dp[i - minJump]){
                reachable++;
            }
            // remove expired index
            if(i - maxJump - 1 >= 0 &&
               dp[i - maxJump - 1]){
                reachable--;
            }
            if(s[i] == '0' &&
               reachable > 0){
                dp[i] = true;
            }
        }
        return dp[n - 1];
    }
};
	Key Insight
Instead of checking all previous positions repeatedly,
we maintain:
		how many reachable indices exist
		inside valid jump range.  
This sliding-window optimization reduces:
		O(n²) → O(n).
